{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01RHCyr4n4YNS2zgsv14royP","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is asking me to analyze a spreadsheet formula engine and write a test plan for 10 behaviors. For each behavior, I need to:\n\n1. Determine the minimum test level (Unit, Integration, System, Agentic, Workflow)\n2. Justify why that level is minimum\n3. Describe what the test would check\n4. Assign confidence probabilities to each level (summing to 1.0)\n5. Verify the test description actually requires that level (plan_consistent check)\n\nLet me work through each behavior systematically.\n\n## Behavior 1: SUM(A1:A10) evaluates correctly\n\nThis is a straightforward formula evaluation for a simple, deterministic built-in function.\n\n**Analysis:**\n- Does a pure in-process mock miss this? No. The SUM function is deterministic and local.\n- Does it depend on OS, real network, or real subprocess? No.\n- Would mocking hide a real failure? No.\n- LLM dependency? No, this is deterministic math.\n- Multi-step agentic? No.\n\n**What could fail:**\n- Off-by-one in range parsing (A1:A10 might be parsed as A1:A9)\n- Incorrect aggregation logic (summing strings, ignoring empty cells, etc.)\n- Type coercion bugs\n\nThis is testable purely at the **Unit** level: create a cell, set A1:A10 values, evaluate the SUM formula, check the result. No integration needed.\n\n**Minimum Level:** Unit\n**Confidence:** Unit=0.95, Integration=0.05 (edge case: might want integration to test with actual cell references wired up, but that's still unit-testable)\n\n## Behavior 2: Cascaded formulas (B1 references A1, cell references B1)\n\nThis tests formula dependency chain.\n\n**Analysis:**\n- Does a pure mock miss this? Possibly. If you mock the cell resolution, you might not test the actual dependency resolution order.\n\n\n- Real infrastructure isn't required, but the formula engine's evaluation logic must be exercised without stubbing out the core resolution mechanism.\n- Mocking could mask failures by returning hardcoded values instead of actually computing the dependency chain.\n\n**What could fail:**\n- Formula evaluation order (must evaluate B1 before the dependent formula)\n- Circular reference in the chain\n- Stale value caching (B1 computed once, then A1 changes, but B1 not re-evaluated)\n\nThis requires **Unit** level testing where you set up cells A1 and B1 with actual formula dependencies and verify the result, rather than mocking the formula engine itself. The test must exercise the real evaluation order without relying on stubbed cell resolution.\n\n**Minimum Level:** Unit\n**Confidence:** Unit=0.85, Integration=0.15 (integration could verify the dependency chain works across multiple formula evaluations in sequence)\n\n## Behavior 3: Circular dependency detection (A1→B1→A1)\n\nTesting error handling when formulas reference each other in a loop.\n\n**Analysis:**\n- Mocking the cycle detection or graph traversal would hide whether the actual detection works.\n- No real infrastructure needed.\n- Could return hardcoded success instead of detecting the cycle.\n\n**What could fail:**\n- Cycle never detected, causing an infinite loop\n- Cycle detected but crashes instead of returning an error\n- Wrong error type returned\n\n**Unit** level testing works here—create the circular reference and verify the proper error is raised.\n\n**Minimum Level:** Unit\n**Confidence:** Unit=0.95, Integration=0.05\n\n## Behavior 4: VLOOKUP exact match and error handling\n\nTesting a lookup function with two distinct outcomes (match found vs. not found).\n\n**Analysis:**\n- Mocking the lookup logic itself would bypass the actual search mechanism.\n- No real infrastructure or LLM dependency.\n\n**What could fail:**\n- Type coercion when converting numbers to strings. This is testable at the unit level.\n\nFor cross-sheet references, the key question is whether the sheet lookup system is mocked or real. If mocked, it could hide failures in reference parsing or sheet context passing. The main risks are sheet-not-found errors, incorrect parsing of the Sheet2!A1 syntax, and whether sheet context gets properly passed during cell evaluation. This could stay at unit level if sheets are all in-memory, but might need integration testing if they're managed as separate modules or loaded dynamically.\n\nRecalculation order depends on the real dependency graph and engine—mocking either one masks whether cells actually evaluate in the correct topological order. The risks include wrong evaluation sequence, cycles causing infinite loops, and cells not being recalculated at all. Testing this requires multiple cells with dependencies, changing one value, and verifying all dependents update correctly.\n\nUndo/redo with formulas needs the actual undo stack and cell storage. Mocking these hides whether formula text is restored correctly, whether dependent values recalculate after undo, or whether the undo stack itself gets corrupted. The test must edit a formula, verify dependents recalculate, undo, then confirm both the formula and its dependents are restored.\n\nSave and load requires real disk I/O—mocking file operations defeats the purpose entirely since it can't catch serialization bugs, format corruption, or data loss during the write-read cycle. high confidence. Disk I/O is OS-level behavior, so System testing is the right fit. None of these scenarios involve LLM calls or AI models—they're purely deterministic operations and data persistence, so Agentic and Workflow levels don't apply here.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13874,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13874},"output_tokens":7,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c1c686ca-e171-42eb-9a29-cbaa01b7cfa5","uuid":"15861dd9-3933-47fd-b7ea-8ba5a2c3706e"}
